{{Infobox scientist | name = Friedrich Otto Rudolf Sturm | image = Rudolf Sturm.jpeg | image_size = | caption = | birth_date = {{birth date|1841|1|6|df=y}} | birth_place = [[Breslau]], [[Kingdom of Prussia|Prussia]] | death_date = {{death date and age|1919|4|12|1841|1|6|df=y}} | death_place = [[Breslau]], [[Weimar Republic|Germany]] | nationality = German | fields = [[Mathematics]] | workplaces = [[University of Breslau]] | alma_mater = [[University of Breslau]] | doctoral_advisor = [[Heinrich Schröter]] | doctoral_students = [[Otto Toeplitz]] | known_for = | awards = }}
'''Friedrich Otto Rudolf Sturm''' (6 January 1841 – 12 April 1919) was a German mathematician. His Ph.D. advisor was [[Heinrich Eduard Schroeter]], and [[Otto Toeplitz]] was one of his Ph.D. students. His best ever proposal type claim is commonly known as "Sturm's Theorem" based on finding the complex imaginary roots of an infinite arbitrary-integer series.
