{{Infobox scientist | name = Irit Dinur | image = | image_size = 150px | caption = Irit Dinur | birth_date = | birth_place = | death_date = | death_place = | residence = | citizenship = | nationality = | ethnicity = | field = [[Computer Science]], [[Computational complexity theory|Complexity Theory]] | work_institution = [[Weizmann Institute of Science]] | alma_mater = Ph.D. [[Tel Aviv University]] | doctoral_advisor = [[Shmuel Safra]] | doctoral_students = | thesis_year = 2001 | known_for = | author_abbreviation_bot = | author_abbreviation_zoo = | prizes = [[Erdős Prize]] <small>(2012)</small> | religion = | footnotes = | website = {{URL|http://www.wisdom.weizmann.ac.il/~dinuri/}} }} '''Irit Dinur''' (Hebrew: אירית דינור) is an [[Israel]]i mathematician. She is professor of computer science at the [[Weizmann Institute of Science]].<ref>[http://www.wisdom.weizmann.ac.il/math/faculty.shtml Faculty listing], Weizmann Institute Faculty of Mathematics and Computer Science, retrieved 2014-06-18.</ref> Her research is in foundations of [[computer science]] and in [[combinatorics]], and especially in [[probabilistically checkable proof]]s and [[hardness of approximation]].<ref>[http://www.wisdom.weizmann.ac.il/math/research.shtml Research interests of faculty members], Weizmann Institute Faculty of Mathematics and Computer Science, retrieved 2014-06-18.</ref> ==Biography== Irit Dinur earned her doctorate in 2002 from the school of computer science in [[Tel-Aviv University]], advised by [[Shmuel Safra]]; her thesis was entitled ''On the Hardness of Approximating the Minimum Vertex Cover and The Closest Vector in a Lattice''.<ref>[http://www.cs.tau.ac.il/thesis/ School of Computer Science Thesis Repository], Tel-Aviv University, accessed 2014-06-18.</ref> She joined the Weizmann Institute after visiting the [[Institute of Advanced Studies]] in [[Princeton, New Jersey]], [[NEC]], and the [[University of California, Berkeley]].
Dinur published in 2006 a new proof of the [[PCP theorem]] that was significantly simpler than previous proofs of the same result.<ref>{{citation | last1 = Radhakrishnan | first1 = Jaikumar | last2 = Sudan | first2 = Madhu | doi = 10.1090/S0273-0979-06-01143-8 | issue = 1 | journal = Bulletin of the American Mathematical Society | mr = 2265009 | pages = 19–61 | series = New Series | title = On Dinur's proof of the PCP theorem | volume = 44 | year = 2007}}.</ref> ==Awards and recognition== In 2007, she was given the [[Michael Bruno]] Memorial Award in Computer Science by [[Yad Hanadiv]].<ref>[http://www.yadhanadiv.org.il/node/616/view/recipients Michael Bruno Memorial Award recipients], retrieved 2014-06-18.</ref> She was a plenary speaker at the 2010 [[International Congress of Mathematicians]].<ref>[https://gowers.wordpress.com/2010/08/30/icm2010-avila-dinur-plenary-lectures/ ICM2010 — Avila, Dinur, plenary lectures], [[Tim Gowers]], August 30, 2010.</ref> In 2012, she won the [[Erdős Prize|Anna and Lajos Erdős Prize in Mathematics]], given by the Israel Mathematical Union.<ref>[http://www.euro-math-soc.eu/node/3117 EMS e-News 4, September 2012], [[European Mathematical Society]], retrieved 2014-06-18.</ref> She was the William Bentinck-Smith Fellow at [[Harvard University]] in 2012–2013.<ref>[https://www.radcliffe.harvard.edu/people/irit-dinur Irit Dinur], Radcliffe Institute for Advanced Study, Harvard University, retrieved 2014-06-18.</ref>
