The '''Thomas Bond Sprague Prize''' is a prize awarded annually to the student or students showing the greatest distinction in [[actuarial science]], [[finance]], [[insurance]], [[operations research|mathematics of operational research]], [[probability theory|probability]], [[risk]] and [[statistics]] in the [[Part III of the Mathematical Tripos|Master of Mathematics/Master of Advanced Studies]] examinations of the [[University of Cambridge]], also known as Part III of the Mathematical Tripos.<ref>http://www.admin.cam.ac.uk/reporter/2011-12/weekly/6273/section12.shtml#heading2-35 Cambridge University Reporter CLXII no 38</ref> The prize is named after [[Thomas Bond Sprague]], the only person to have been president of both the [[Institute of Actuaries]] in London and the [[Faculty of Actuaries]] in Edinburgh. It is awarded by the [[Rollo Davidson Prize|Rollo Davidson Trust]]<ref>http://www.statslab.cam.ac.uk/Rollo/index.html Rollo Davidson Trust</ref> of [[Churchill College, Cambridge]], following a donation by D. O. Forfar, MA, FFA, FRSE (alumnus of Trinity College, Cambridge), former Appointed [[Actuary]] of [[Scottish Widows]].<ref>http://www.theactuary.com/news/2012/08/social-news-round-up-august-2012/ The Actuary, August 2012, p. 17</ref>
